Its really frustrating how the mapbox SDK v10 is setup for Kotlin and seemingly little thought to how Java users can access it.  I found a workaround for this issue by creating a Kotlin helper class which I can call from Java in order to access the syntax required:
```
class KtNonsense {
    companion object {
        fun doTheThing(mapView: MapView, act: AppCompatActivity) {
            val locationComponentPlugin = mapView.location
            locationComponentPlugin.updateSettings {
                this.enabled = true
                this.locationPuck = LocationPuck2D(
                        bearingImage = AppCompatResources.getDrawable(
                                act, //this@LocationTrackingActivity,
                                R.drawable.mapbox_user_puck_icon,
                        ),
                        shadowImage = AppCompatResources.getDrawable(
                                act, //this@LocationTrackingActivity,
                                R.drawable.mapbox_user_icon_shadow,
                        ),
                        scaleExpression = interpolate {
                            linear()
                            zoom()
                            stop {
                                literal(0.0)
                                literal(0.6)
                            }
                            stop {
                                literal(20.0)
                                literal(1.0)
                            }
                        }.toJson()
                )
            }
        }
    }
}
```
and then can call that within the Java Activity class like this:
```
 KtNonsense.Companion.doTheThing( mapView, this );
```
This activates the user location &#39;puck&#39; for me.   Note, I also implemented the required permission request for FINE and COARSE LOCATION in the normal java way 
```
        if( ActivityCompat.checkSelfPermission( this, android.Manifest.permission.ACCESS_FINE_LOCATION ) != PackageManager.PERMISSION_GRANTED )
...
```
and I also registered a LocationManager to get updates back to my activity - I use this to set the Camera location for the map on the first update
```
           locationManager.requestLocationUpdates( LocationManager.GPS_PROVIDER, 1000, 0, this );
```
Also note, having only been using Java before, I had to add Kotlin compilation plugin to my build.gradle (I think it has to be before the com.android.application plugin so it will compile the kotlin first (in build.gradle at app level):
```
apply plugin: &#39;kotlin-android&#39;
apply plugin: &#39;com.android.application&#39;
```
and also in build.gradle at project level:
```
...
buildscript {
...
   dependencies {
        classpath &quot;org.jetbrains.kotlin:kotlin-gradle-plugin:1.8.21&quot;
...
```
Anyway - that got it working for me.  If there are any Mapbox devs reading this - is there a better way?  Can you make an easier way to access your product from Java?

